# Rust Patterns for Roguebusters

## Encapsulation via Traits

Use traits for shared behavior, not code duplication:

```rust
// ✅ GOOD — polymorphism through traits
pub trait UIElement {
    fn render(&self, ctx: &mut BTerm, state: &GameState);
}

// ❌ BAD — copying render logic into each UI struct
```

## Components Are Pure Data

Components hold state only — no methods beyond simple accessors:

```rust
// ✅ GOOD
#[derive(Component)]
#[storage(VecStorage)]
pub struct Attributes {
    pub strength: i32,
    pub agility: i32,
}

// ❌ BAD — logic in a component
impl Attributes {
    pub fn apply_damage(&mut self, ...) { ... }  // this belongs in a system
}
```

## Systems Are Pure Behavior

Systems read/write components and resources. They do not own state. Declare only what the system truly needs — two systems sharing a `WriteStorage` for the same component cannot run in parallel:

```rust
pub struct MySystem;
impl<'a> System<'a> for MySystem {
    type SystemData = (
        ReadStorage<'a, Position>,   // prefer Read over Write where possible
        WriteStorage<'a, Attributes>,
        Read<'a, GameState>,
        // ❌ don't pull in storages the system doesn't use
    );
    fn run(&mut self, (pos, mut attrs, state): Self::SystemData) { ... }
}
```

## Visibility

- Default to private (`pub(crate)` or no `pub`)
- Only expose what crosses a module boundary
- Resources in `GameState` are the cross-cutting exception

## Naming

- `snake_case` for modules, functions, variables
- `PascalCase` for types, traits, enums
- Systems: noun phrase (`PlayerAction`, `NPCBehavior`, `SimplePath`)
- Components: noun, describes what the entity *has* (`Position`, `Combatant`, `Inventory`)

## Error Handling

- Use `Option`/`Result` — never `unwrap()` in game loop paths
- Prefer `if let` / `match` over `.unwrap()` or `.expect()` in hot paths
